description.text:
This is another one of those spiral vases you see around on thingiverse, however what makes this different to all of the others is that this was modelled, not scripted. When printing this vase actually has 2 walls, the exterior wall and then an interior forming the inside of the vase where your stuff goes, thus making it reasonably watertight.
The inside diameter also varies in width in accordance to the outside, basically if the outside gets wider so will the inside and if the outside gets narrower so will the inside.

One last thing about this model, since I exported directly from blender, it has a stupid scale. So once you import the model into Cura (which takes a while, I like lots of polys) you need to scale it up a lot, good thing about this, just rotate it so the bottom is facing down and the scale to any height you want.

If you guys feel generous then why not have a look at what I offer on shapeways, who doesn't want a mixer made for a drill ?

description.text:
This is a remix of my original design. I designed a jet drive a while back and also got a "new" printer that has a Z of around 300mm. Decided to add the jet drive to the hull and print the largest boat hull I could on my printer. Ended up being a 22mm jet drive stuffed in to a 285mm long boat hull. added a flat area on top for an easy hatch. Printed it hollow with 2 perimeters set to .75mm for a total wall thickness of 1.4mm so it has some layer overlap for adhesion. Printed in esun PETG. Did one test in a sink and it works pretty well. Waiting on parts to finish it.

Now have all the files for the jet drive loaded. Here is what i am using for parts and electronics.

  • 1/8" stainless steel drive shaft purchased from McMaster (3mm would likely also work)
  • K&S brass tubing from hobby shop to use as stuffing tube and bushing in stator. ID to match shaft size
  • I used a 5g servo for steering with some 1mm wire
  • motor and esc from banggood. currently using a DYS 2000kv outrunner. probably too low of KV. Also working on a 4800kv ducted motor that they sell there as well.
  • ESC was just a 10a mini quad ESC
  • I was running it with a 2s 350ma lipo but I would recommend 3s if using the 2000kv motor

I drew up and made a motor mount that was laser cut from birch ply. I may add that file as a printable part. Also used a laser to cut the top hatch out. I included a few different 22mm impellers I have played around with.

Printer:

Mankati Fullscale XT

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.3mm

Infill:

none

Notes:

.3mm layer height, .75mm layer width with 2 shells and no infill. PETG, 235C at the nozzle, 60C on the bed. Hairspray on glass for adhesion.

title: V9 Extruder Upgrade for MK7 Drive Gear

description.text: The http://mendel-parts.com V9 1,75mm Hotend/Extruder works reliable as it is, but it has some downsides. It uses a brass drive gear which is not very reliable. If the filaments runs out or snaps the teeth of the brass drive gear touch the hardened steel surface of the bearing and become dull. Also filament change is complicated and time consuming. It is often necessary to disassemble the screws that hold the springs if you don't have 3 hands. ;-) The MK7 Drive Gear is a useful upgrade. It has a better grip on the filament, is made from stainless steel and makes filament change easy. The enhanced driveholder guides the filament more reliable and can be fixed down to the lower aluminum plate to increase stability. To fit the MK7 Drive Gear on an V9 Extruder some modifications are necessary:

• Print extruder_corner_small.stl and driverholder_enhanced.stl, the other parts are optional, V9_extruder_filament_guide_MK7_2.stl is usefull if you plan to print with 1.75mm ABS (see http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:16319 for instructions)
  • Drill out holes if necessary. It is important the the screws which hold the springs can move freely.
  • Remove old driverholder, the left extruder corner and the brass insert.
  • Attach the MK7 Drive Gear to the motor shaft.
  • Readjust the motor position, so that the groove in the drive gear lines up with the hotend entrance.
  • Attach the smaller extruder corner.
  • Attach the new driverholder.
    7a. Optional: Drill a 4mm hole through the aluminum plate, to fix down the driverholder with an additional screw.
  • Attach the idler with the 4 springs an screws.
    • Optional:

  • See http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:16319 for the optional filament guide which is useful for printing with 1.75mm ABS.

  • Print out the extruder_wheel.stl and press in the old brass insert. The wheel can be attached to the back of the motor shaft and is useful for changing filament.
    • You can now insert the filament by slightly pushing it in and turning the wheel. It isn't necessary to press against the springs anymore. Comments/suggestions are appreciated.

comments.text:
The first 1-1/2 year I printed over 1200m of PLA with my V9 extruder with brass insert, no problem.
Last summer I got the problem that my PLA was cut in two by the insert because it was warn out and became sharp edged.
I filed down the sharp edges and now it is printing flowless again.

title: The spider spool (collapsible parametric filament reel holder)

description.text:
This is an openscad rewrite of the clever filament holder by Boardofdenver, now fully parametrized to accomodate any diameter. With the customizer you can tweak all the geometry: thickness, number of arms, segment lengths, angles and so...
Here is a video of the thing: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tNVpsIQXVbE
I also added two holes on each branch to lock the other end of the filament (check the close-up with the blue filament).
You will find two predefined geometries, you can mix the hubs and arms but use two same hubs (and of course one kind of arms!)
By default they rotate on a M8 rod (eg. with http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:137602 for the ultimaker)

Printed with ~2mm walls and 30% infill. Use more arms for bigger or heavier spools, 3 sets of arms is usually enough (ie. 3x2=6 parts, since the branches are all the same). You need also two prints of a given hub.  
Note that you can also define a fake spool temporarily to adjust the arms.  
I use it with my minimalist spool holder and my customizable thumb nuts (check the references).

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This model is pretty much to scale, so if printed too small, it will likely end up with spiderweb wings. This was printed on a Form 2 by a friend, so I'd recommend modifying the file yourself to thicken the wings if your printer just wont do it.

Update: Version 2 is uploaded to fix the issues with the wings.

If you enjoy the model and would be so kind to support me monatarily for my work please consider supporting here: https://www.patreon.com/oranhunter

Methodology

I used Blender to model this aircraft. I take a minimalist approach to modeling. I attempt to use as few vertices as possible and use a tool in blender to do the smoothing out of shapes for me. The end result is a mesh that's as accurate as I can get it and still maintain printability. The F-117 is obviously very geometric so it doesn't necessarily require an extreme amount of work to shape it out using line drawings.

Check out my channel for tips and timelapses.

description.text: This is a desktop "hutch" which I built to reclaim some real estate on my computer/3d printing desk. It is supporting a very heavy roland speaker and a very light phone. The zip ties you see are holding in some 12v led lights and are not part of the build. The hutch consists of four corner brackets (you have to print four), and interlocking square pipes or tubes (you will have to print six). I have enclosed a variety of tubes from 60mm to 300mm. Instead of printing a surface I designed a "truss" which can be printed out as needed. My particular "hutch" is 125mm tall, 250mm long, and 110mm wide (60mm pipe+25mm corner+25mm corner +4.. mm pipe diameter) . The truss I am using is designed to bridge a 60mm tube. I have enclosed a truss for use with a 60mm, 80mm, and 100mm tube. The only suggestion I would have is to align the corners so the layer lines are parallel to the surface. This way the layers lines will be in compression.

title: Geiger counter case for DIY kit

description.text:
Case for cheap DIY Geiger counter kit (available from aliexpress and others) with arduino and misc modules. Was a fun little project.
If you have a UV sensitive tube like mine I recommend using some kapton tape over the grill - blocks UV completely and seems to still let beta through reasonably well.

Insert slide switch first, then screw the Geiger board into place with some standoffs. Screw/jam the pushbutton in place, then attach the rest of the hardware with generous amounts of hotsnot glue - for that extra professional look..

The arduino sketch I'm running is a remix of Majek's nice code (link in my code comments) with added support for bluetooth + misc hacks/spaghetti, menu toggles and and options.
Code available here:
https://github.com/noianet/arduino/blob/master/Geiger_Counter_simple_model_NGMC_V1_LCD/Geiger_Counter_simple_model_NGMC_V1_LCD.ino

Runs ~8hrs with bluetooth logging enabled and LCD backlight disabled on the ancient "1100mAh" Nokia battery I found in the junk bin and hacked into place - not too bad for code not optimized for powersaving and that (cheap) power hungry bluetooth module I used.

I've been doing a lot of sanding due to minimal errors between some of my dessigns and the caliber tool. When there are some decimals on the caliber and you have to choose how to round them up I find myself having choosen the wrong values. So I thought, why not have some templates to check if the bearing will fit with a snap... or some aluminium profiles I'm currently using will slip into the holes or supports.

It's a really easy dessign and I've included the FreeCAD file incase anyone wishes to contribute.

Nothing really special, just saves some money or time when you have to round up some decimals to fit the accurracy of your printer.

Currently:

  • 8.0 through 8.4 radius. (For example: Used for 625zz bearing)
  • Aluminium profiles: 6x6m to 6.5x6.5mm, 8x8 to 8.5x8.5mm and 10x12mm to 10.5x12.5mm

description.text:
It's time to get organized with these roomy shelf units. They're a perfect fit for any slotted Wall Control metal pegboards. Use them for storing everything, like shop supplies, 3D printer filament spools, boots, or other heavy and bulky items. Shelf surfaces include both large and small scale holes that make organizing most any size tools.

Wall Control metal pegboards are strong, durable, and look great - making them a common addition to garages and workshops everywhere. These 8 inch deep shelf units, which vary from 5 to 13 inches in length, are compatible with all slotted Wall Control pegboards that are 4 inches or more in height. Two or more shelves can be installed next to each other horizontally, leaving a space of about 2 mm between units.

These shelves are relatively large. So I've listed this Thing on eBay for those who find it to be too big for their printer.

If you have Wall Control pegboards in your shop then you should also check out this parts storage rack Thing here on Thingiverse, and this mounting system for your Chargepoint EV Charger on eBay.

Come on, get your life together!

Printer:

gMax 1.5+ XT

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

15%

Installing on pegboard

This Thing is compatible with all Wall Control metal pegboards with slots and 4 inches in height or taller. Two short Wall Control brackets are needed to install the rack onto the pegboard, However 3 of these brackets are needed for the largest, 13 X 8 inch version.

Begin by slipping the top portion of each bracket into the slits on the back of the unit. The brackets need to rotate counter-clockwise as the turned up portion finds its way into the slit of the shelf. The bottom of the bracket might need a little bit extra convincing, which you can give them by pushing them against a hard surface. Just be careful that the bracket is following the internal path. See the photo of this Thing for comparison.

Now that you've fitted the brackets into the shelf, remove the brackets and install them into to properly spaced slots of the pegboard. With the shelf at a 45-degree angle relative to the pegboard, allow the turned-up part of both brackets to find the same top-most opening that you'd previously slipped them into. Making sure that the top back of the shelf remains against the pegboard, rotate the shelf down until both the top and bottom of the shelf's back are flush against the pegboard.

And you're done.

title: Flower Iris Box
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A functional Iris Box with six rotating doors.
You can find all my new box designs on my MyMiniFactory profile : https://www.myminifactory.com/users/Brien%20Allison
The box is opened and closed by turning the dimpled collar which moves the doors with connecting links.
The box is printed in separate pieces which are then assembled and the hinges clip together.
An interesting aspect of this box is that if the parts fit together well it can be opened with one hand. It is also strangely proficient at catching insects and spiders.
You MUST print the parts (unscaled) with 0.3mm layer height otherwise the hinges will not work (see below).
You could try scaling the model down 2/3 and printing at 0.2 mm layer height although I have yet to try this myself.
No supports are required for this print.

Printer:

Anet A6

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3mm layer height

Infill:

30%

Step 1 Test prints

Some parts have two versions, 1 and 2 which correspond to 0.4mm and 0.3mm tolerances for the hinge parts. This is because the hinge dimensions can vary slightly depending on printer type, settings or filament used.
It doesn't matter greatly if the link-door and link-collar hinges are a little loose, but it is important that the door-container hinges are a good fit, to hold the mechanism together.
First print the container and door 1 and 2.
The unaltered STL files MUST be printed with a layer height of 0.3 mm for the hinges to work, as the hinges clip together using ridges which vary with 0.3mm layers.
Then test the door-container hinges by pressing them together slightly, but not fully. The hinges should be held securely together but not be too tight as to be hard to turn. Take note of which door fits better, for me it was door 2.
Let me know if you need parts with larger or smaller hinge tolerances than those provided.

Step 2 Printing

Then go ahead and print all the parts required (6 links, 6 doors, 1 collar and 1 container). Print collar 1 if door 1 was a better fit for the hinges or collar 2 if door 2 was better.
No supports are required for the parts.
The bottom surface of the door while printing is the top of the box so make sure the first layer is very neat if you want a nice top finish for the box. You could use a raft for this which would also stop 'elephants foot' on the bottom of the door, making them fit together better during assembly. I would recommend a filament with good dimensional accuracy for printing such as PLA.

Step 3 Assembly

Firstly place the collar onto the container. Then fit all the links onto the collar. The links MUST be assembled with the pointed end pointing anti-clockwise otherwise the box won't open. Then clip all the doors into place (see assembly picture).
Even within the same print, some of the hinges can vary. You may want to try different parts together to see which fit the best. Due to the overlapping nature of the mechanism, it helps hold the mechanism together if some parts are loose, it can also make adding the last door a bit tricky. The tolerances for the model assembly are 0.3mm.

title: Telescopic Pvc Tripod For Studio Light

description.text:
Hello, this is my second post on thingverse, a 3d printed telescopic tripod with for studio light. The goal was to use the cheapest ( between 5€ and 10€ per tripod ) and robust material with easy cutting.

/!\ Before purchasing pvc pipes print at least a feet for the 32 mm pipes and the anti wobble for the 42mm pipe because sometimes it wont feet due to bad wall thickness.

Video of the assembly : https://youtu.be/a48VfIzF55U

Printer:

Dagoma DiscoEasy 200

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

17%

Notes:

Use the custom support i made for feet / base / studio light adaptator.

1. After printing the piece your need to take the 32 mm pipe and cut it :
    . 3 piece of 30 cm long
    . 1 piece left of 110 cm long
  2. Take the 40 mm tube and cut it at 70 cm long
  3. Put the 3 feet on the 32 mm / 30 cm pipes
  4. Put the 3 32 mm / 30 cm pipe on the base
  5. Put the 40 mm pipe on the base
  6. Put the anti wobble tube on the top of the 40mm pipe
  7. Put the last feet on the 32mm / 110 cm pipe
  8. Put the 32 mm / 110 cm pipe trough the anti wobble tube
  9. Put a M6 nut on the small clamp
  10. Put a M6 L30 bolt on the cap and screw it a bit on the small clamp
  11. Put the clamp trough the 32mm / 110 cm pipe
  12. Put the Studio light adaptator on the top of the 32 mm / 110 cm pipe

Recommandations :

. Print at least one feet and the base / anti wobble before purchasing pvc pipes
. Screw the cap to hold the pod in high positon
. You can make smaller / bigger tripod if you want.
. You can put cement / salt / weight inside the 32 mm / 30 cm feet for better stability

. Todo :

. Big clamp for the 40 mm pipe with adaptater on the 32mm to hold various object like a smartphone or a light reflector
. Some other stuff ( give ideas on comments )
I designed this object on fusion 360 from autodesk

. Base : 54 g / 4h40 | 0.2 mm layer, 17% fill, custom support

description.text:
This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/euO6IEV2azc

These are made to be surface mounted as if you were using an aluminum part. Paint the parts individually first before assembling them. They glue up easy using some simple Cyanoacrylate glue (Brand names: Crazy Glue, Super Glue). I bought my glue at the dollar store. After painting you will start with the small caps, snap them into place and then glue it down. Then take the large pocket align it on a small edge and put a drop of glue on the rim to set ONLY one of the short sides in place. Once that drop sets then you will roll the large vented part over the rest of the pocket and it will take the proper curve shape. Tack that end down with glue and also let it set. Once dry you can add a few more drops of glue along the long edge of the pocket apply pressure to the vented face so it glues up nice and tight. Test fit your part to the skins of the astromech and sand the edges if needed to make it fit. ENJOY!!

Working on 3d printable versions of the RC4WD parts for their 1/18 Gelande D90 truck, along with a few additional parts

will update when I can.

Current parts include:

  • Side rails (under rear windows)
  • square ladder for rear
  • slightly rounded ladder for rear
  • body lifting front bumper (will add a rear bumper soon)
  • Rear Tire Cover
  • Future plans include:
  • Internal wheel wells
  • body risers (non bumper versions)
  • Interior
  • Roof rack (in the works currently awaiting print and testing)
  • Brush guard
  • wheel flares
  • front and rear bolt on bumpers (non body lift versions)

5/30/17

  • Added Dual motor mount (tested correct but may need a little trimming to fit)
  • Added Riser bumpers, (slots cutout for 8mm magnet insert, to mount body with magnets!)
  • Corrected Tire cover to be all caps.

6/1/17

  • Added a thicker rear bumper as the first one was pretty flush with the body.
  • added a untested Bumper + brush bar. I may break this into two printable pieces.

6/7/17

  • added a new front bumper that should fit with the lifted body.
  • Added rock "rock sliders" that should fit the body lift. and possibly stock when flipped.
  • Added snorkel

6/20/17

  • Added alternative lifted rear bumper
  • Added THICK rear lifted bumper
  • Added lift front bumper without winch
  • added a untested no lift bolt on front bumper (you'll need LONG screws for this!)
  • Added Offroad style rear bumper
  • Added a thicker bodylift version of the rock sliders
  • Added a solid Bodylift version of rock Sliders
  • Added Solid spare tire for easier printing.
  • REMOVED original front bumper, it didn't fit correctly.

As always! post a comment with issues or suggestions!
